Function Names
The name of the function is chosen by the author.


add_two &lt;- function(x){

  return(x + 2)

}










Function names have no inherent meaning.


The name you give to a function does not affect what the function does.

add_three &lt;- function(x){
  return(x + 7)
}


add_three(5)

[1] 12

Body: {  }
The body of the function is where the action happens.

The body must be specified within a set of curly brackets.
The code in the body will be executed (in order) whenever the function is called.


add_something &lt;- function(x, something = 2){
  x + something
}

Output: return()
If you are coming to R from a background in Python, C, or Java then an explicit return may feel more natural to you.


add_something &lt;- function(x, something = 2){
  return(x + something)
}

Function Style – Using return()s


“Only use return() for early returns. Otherwise, rely on R to return the result of the last evaluated expression.”





safe_square &lt;- function(x) {
  if (!is.numeric(x)) return(NA)
  x^2
}

Make it into a function!

every_third &lt;- function(x) {

  x[ 
  seq_along(x) %% 3 == 1
  ]

  }

Input Validation
When a function requires an input of a specific data type, check that the supplied argument is valid.

stopifnot()if() + stop()Multiple validations




add_something &lt;- function(x, something){
  stopifnot(is.numeric(x))
  return(x + something)
}

add_something(x = "statistics", something = 5)

Error in `add_something()`:
! is.numeric(x) is not TRUE







add_something &lt;- function(x, something){
  if(!is.numeric(x)){
    stop("Please provide a numeric input for the x argument.")
  }
  return(x + something)
}

add_something(x = "statistics", something = 5)

Error in `add_something()`:
! Please provide a numeric input for the x argument.






How would you modify the previous code to validate both x and something?
Meaning, the function should check if both x and something are numeric.

Multiple Validations

Option 1: if() + stop()Option 2: stopifnot()



add_something &lt;- function(x, something){
  if(!is.numeric(x) | !is.numeric(something)){
    stop("Please provide numeric inputs for both arguments.")
  }
  return(x + something)
}

add_something(x = 2, something = "R")

Error in `add_something()`:
! Please provide numeric inputs for both arguments.





add_something &lt;- function(x, something){
  stopifnot(is.numeric(x), is.numeric(something))
  return(x + something)
}

add_something(x = 2, something = "R")

Error in `add_something()`:
! is.numeric(something) is not TRUE

Part Four: Making Drink Modifications

Oh no! Tidy Roasters has run out of soy milk. The baRistas decide to use oat milk instead. In the coffee_orders dataframe, change all the soy milk requests to oat milk. Use the if_else() function from dplyr to do this.








Tip



Hint 1: Remember, you can find the documentation for a specific function by running ?FUNCTION_NAME in the console.
Hint 2: Remember to save the updated Milk back into the coffee_orders dataframe! This is the same step you used in last week’s PA!





coffee_orders$Milk &lt;- if_else(condition = coffee_orders$Milk == "soy",
                              true = "oat",
                              false = coffee_orders$Milk)



The baRistas need to know how much ice to have on hand. For a medium iced drink, they need 4oz of ice. For a large iced drink, they need 6oz of ice. Use a for() loop and conditionals to calculate the total ice amount the baRistas need.



ice &lt;- 0
for (i in 1:num_orders) {
  if (coffee_orders$Temperature[i] == "iced") {
    if (coffee_orders$Size[i] == "medium") {
      ice &lt;- ice + 4
    }
    else {
      ice &lt;- ice + 6
    }
  }
}
